{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module-to-client handoff (request builder -> API adapter), so Unit can miss wiring errors (wrong field name, dropped labels). REAL-INFRA is not required: a stub client that captures outbound payload reproduces the failure. Rejected higher levels: System is disqualified because behavior text only requires request content, not real network/OS/subprocess; Agentic is disqualified because correctness does not depend on model judgment/output.","test_description":"Wire the classifier module to a fake in-process API client, invoke classify(doc,taxonomy), and assert captured outbound request contains the full taxonomy label list exactly once in the expected request field.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.7,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Behavior is about response handoff boundary (API response parser/adapter -> module return contract). A pure Unit test of a helper normalizer may miss integration defects in response extraction path. No REAL-INFRA needed; stub API response is enough. Rejected higher levels: System disqualified (no real network needed), Agentic disqualified (test injects explicit invalid label; no model-quality dependence).","test_description":"Use a fake API client returning a successful response payload with label=\"nonsense_label\" and taxonomy lacking it; assert classify(...) returns \"unknown\" and never surfaces the raw invalid label.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"This is explicitly one-function deterministic normalization logic; no module handoff is required by the behavior text. MOCK-MISS does not apply because failure is local algorithmic determinism. Rejected higher levels: Integration/System/Agentic are disqualified by behavior text \"identical raw API responses\" and focus on normalization step only.","test_description":"Call the normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixture (including case/whitespace variants embedded identically per run) and assert output label is identical across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency of model-returned labels; correctness depends on real model outputs/non-determinism. Mocking would hide this failure class. MULTI-STEP does not apply: this is repeated single-step classification, not a chained multi-agent pipeline. Rejected higher level: Workflow is disqualified because behavior text does not describe multiple agentic stages with dependent handoffs.","test_description":"Run N live classifications for identical (document,taxonomy) under stable prompt/config, record provider raw responses and final labels, and fail if labels diverge when provider response content is unchanged.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.0,"Integration":0.02,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.85,"Workflow":0.03}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure appears at policy-enforcement-to-dispatch boundary (budget checker + dispatcher). A Unit test of token math alone can miss that oversized requests are still sent. No real OS/network required; in-process fake client can assert dispatch/no-dispatch and payload size. Rejected higher levels: System disqualified (no real network requirement in behavior), Agentic disqualified (no dependence on model output content).","test_description":"Configure small budget, run classify with over-budget document against fake client, and assert module either truncates to policy-compliant size before send or rejects without dispatch, per configured policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"Provider-reported token usage for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"This requires a real AI API call and provider-side token accounting; stubs can trivially pass and hide tokenizer/model-side drift. Per LLM-DEP rule, real AI/ML API-path behaviors default Agentic unless purely transport plumbing; here assertion targets provider usage outcome itself, not only routing. Rejected higher level: Workflow disqualified because only one model call outcome is validated, not multi-stage agentic chaining.","test_description":"Execute live classification on representative document(s), read provider-reported usage from response metadata, and assert total tokens <= configured budget threshold for each call.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.25,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"When the API signals that the request rate is too high, the module waits and retries rather than returning an error to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is retry orchestration across modules (error classifier, backoff policy, retry loop, API client). In-process fakes can reproduce 429/rate-limit signals and verify wait+retry behavior. Rejected higher levels: System disqualified because behavior text does not require real network timing semantics; Agentic disqualified because correctness is infrastructure retry logic, not model output quality.","test_description":"Use a fake client that returns rate-limit error on first call and success on second, with controllable clock/sleeper; assert module performs a wait/backoff, retries, and ultimately returns successful label instead of bubbling error.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.75,"System":0.18,"Agentic":0.05,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
